  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the advantages of mean, median, and mode?",
  "response": "Mean, median, and mode are three measures of central tendency used in statistics to summarize and describe a set of data. Each measure has its own advantages depending on the context and nature of the data. Here's a breakdown of the advantages of each:\n\n### Mean\n1. **Efficiency**: The mean uses all the data points in the set, which can provide a more accurate representation of the \"average\" in cases where the data is symmetrically distributed.\n2. **Mathematical Properties**: The mean has useful mathematical properties that facilitate further statistical analysis, including ease of use in formulae and analyses such as variance and standard deviation.\n3. **Sensitivity to Changes**: The mean is sensitive to every value in the dataset, so it gives an immediate reflection if there\u2019s a change in any data point.\n\n### Median\n1. **Robustness to Outliers**: The median is less affected by extreme values (outliers) compared to the mean. This makes the median a better measure of central tendency for skewed distributions or datasets with outliers.\n2. **Simple Interpretation**: It is often easier to understand, especially in ordinal datasets, since it represents the middle value of a sorted list.\n3. **Applicable to Ordinal Data**: The median can be used with ordinal data, whereas the mean requires interval or ratio data.\n\n### Mode\n1. **Most Common Value**: The mode indicates the value that appears most frequently in a dataset, providing insight into the most common or popular observation.\n2. **Useful for Categorical Data**: The mode is the only measure of central tendency that can be used with nominal data (categories) where neither the mean nor the median is applicable.\n3. **Highlighting Patterns**: Identifying the mode allows for understanding patterns and trends, especially in response or preference data in surveys.\n\n### Summary\n- **Mean**: Best for normally distributed data and enables further statistical analysis.\n- **Median**: Best when dealing with skewed distributions or outliers; provides a central value that is not affected by extreme scores.\n- **Mode**: Highlights the most frequent observation; useful for categorical data.\n\nChoosing the right measure of central tendency depends on the specific characteristics of your data and the analysis you aim to conduct.",
